<?xml version='1.0' standalone='yes'?>

<PLUGIN name="unraid-aicliagents" author="John White" version="2026.05.12.02" launch="Settings/AICliAgentsManager" pluginURL="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johnpwhite/unraid-plg-aicliagents/main/unraid-aicliagents.plg" min="7.2.0" support="https://forums.unraid.net/topic/197460-plugin-support-unraid-tab-for-ai-cli-coding-agents-gemini-cli-claude-code-opencode-kilo-code-pi-coder-codex-cli-factory-droid-cli-copilot-nano-coder/" icon="assets/icons/google-gemini.png">

<CHANGES>
## 2026.05.12.02
- Fix: Upgrading an agent while one of its workspace sessions is open no longer strands that session. Some agents (e.g. Claude Code 2.1.x) have replaced their legacy "cli.js" entry point with a native binary; the launch now re-checks the agent's binary on every relaunch rather than using the path resolved when the session was opened, so an in-place upgrade is picked up automatically. (If a session was already stranded by such an upgrade, close and reopen that workspace once and it will pick up the new binary.)
- Improve: After a plugin install or upgrade, the agent Store cards now show each uninstalled agent's available version straight away — a background version-cache refresh runs on install, so you no longer have to press "Check for Updates" first.

## 2026.05.12.01
- Feat: Environment &amp; secrets management. Every agent's Store card and every workspace now has an "Environment" panel covering general env vars AND API keys/secrets, with full add / edit / delete for both. Secrets are masked and stored separately under tightened (0600) permissions; general vars are managed more loosely. Per-workspace values override the per-agent defaults, and values apply automatically to newly opened terminal sessions ("hot-apply") with no workspace rebuild. Agents that ship default env vars seed them on install as an editable starting set. Replaces the old hardcoded-only API-key vault (the Config-tab "Secrets Vault" card is removed); clearing a value via the UI now actually clears it.
- Feat: Per-agent and per-workspace CLI arguments. A new "Args" panel on each Store card sets default extra flags for that agent (e.g. --max-turns 5), and a workspace can override them in its drawer. Arguments are validated against shell metacharacters. Changing args while a session is open offers "Apply now" — the agent is reloaded in place (Ctrl-C + relaunch) with the new flags, no destroy/recreate.
- Feat: Auto-launch workspaces. A per-workspace toggle in the Terminal panel marks a workspace to start its session automatically — on page load, and after an agent install or upgrade — so your usual workspaces come back without clicking through.
- Feat: Agent Store cards redesigned. Each agent is now one card with five progressive-disclosure panels: Channel, Environment/Secrets, Runtime (RAM, storage stats), Terminal (tmux), and Storage. tmux settings have four tiers of precedence — built-in then agent default then workspace override then a .conf escape hatch — with only divergent keys persisted. Per-agent secret schemas can carry multiple fields (Goose, for instance, registers Provider / Model / provider keys).
- Feat: Two new agents — Goose (Block) and Qwen Code — plus a new agent-source framework so the plugin can manage tools that aren't published to npm (GitHub-release binaries, curl-installers, tarballs), not just npm packages.
- Feat: Workspace resume. Closing a workspace from the drawer now captures the agent's resume id — a printed UUID, a named session, or, for agents like OpenCode that print nothing, the most recent id from their own session database — and offers a "Resume" button next to "Start Fresh" the next time you open a session on that path. Wide tmux capture plus retries so long resume lines aren't truncated.
- Feat: Graceful agent upgrades. Installing or upgrading an agent now enumerates and cleanly closes the active workspace sessions for that agent first (preserving each session's resume id) before swapping the binary, instead of yanking it out from under running terminals. The install/upgrade button warns you with the list of sessions that will be closed; the New Workspace overlay greys out agents whose install is in progress; the install-progress panel appears immediately on click.
- Feat: Cold-start loading overlay. The terminal shows a spinner, the agent icon and a "Starting [agent]..." message for the whole cold-start window (most of which is the agent's own startup) instead of a blank terminal, dismissing as soon as the agent produces output.
- Improve: Storage robustness overhaul. A background storage daemon now owns all SquashFS bake/consolidate work, so the UI never blocks on storage I/O and the "syncing..." indicator clears reliably (it polls real state instead of guessing on a timer). Every layer write is atomic and checksum-verified. On boot your persisted layers are integrity-checked: corruption, missing layers, or a path/host mismatch is detected, you're notified, workspace access is held until it's resolved, and — where a copy survives in a backup/migrated sibling directory — a one-click "Restore" rebuilds from it. Un-baked data is monitored with graduated thresholds. Fixed a class of silent data loss where resume ids, workspace records or agent credentials written during a consolidation cycle could be discarded when the in-memory layer was wiped after the bake. Auto-consolidation now defers while the terminal is busy and runs when idle, so deltas no longer pile up indefinitely on the home stack. Writes to the Flash drive — API keys, plugin config, layer manifests — are forced to disk on every change so they survive an abrupt reboot instead of lingering in the OS page cache. The old per-user sync daemon is retired.
- Fix: ZRAM storage initialisation now works on Unraid 7.2.x and other kernels where zram is built in — a capability probe (/sys/class/zram-control, /dev/zram0) replaces the fatal modprobe zram, with an mkfs.xfs fallback when mkfs.ext4-on-block-device isn't available. Resolves the install failure reported in GitHub issue #5.
- Fix: Agent version display. The Plugins "Update" card and the Store-card version badge showed v0.0.0 / "v?" for most installed agents on a fresh boot, because version discovery was reading package.json from an overlay that wasn't mounted yet. It now mounts on demand and reads the real semver, and a one-shot backfill repairs the registry on upgrade. The version picker also now filters pre-release tags out of the Stable channel correctly and reliably installs the version you pick — downgrade, reinstall and pick-specific-version were no-ops on the redesigned cards.
- Fix: Persistence paths on custom Unraid pools (ZFS pools, user-named cache pools) are accepted instead of rejected with a misleading "outside allowed prefixes" error; stopping the array is no longer blocked by terminals holding a working directory under /mnt/user (the array-stop event is handled, not just full shutdown); installed agents resolve on the main Unraid shell and web terminal (goose, qwen etc. wrappers in /usr/local/bin, and the workspace terminal PATH includes every installed agent's bin directory).
- Fix: UI polish — web fonts now load (the @import was mid-stylesheet, which browsers silently drop); Chrome no longer autofills the agent search box with "root" and hides every card; the "Leave site?" dialog no longer pops when navigating away from the terminal tab; the Plugins page now shows the support-thread link and a plugin description.
- Fix: Per-agent launch reliability — Claude Code's native binary layout, Codex-CLI's vendored Rust binary, OpenCode's cache-directory creation, Goose's first-run TUI prompt, Qwen Code's binary path, and fast-exit handling so a mis-configured agent shows its error instead of relaunch-looping; Node and npm caches are kept on tmpfs and never written to the Flash drive; broadened post-install cleanup of stale /tmp artifacts; XML-escaping fixes in the installer/uninstaller hooks.

## 2026.04.16.27
- Fix: Migration script wrote home sqsh to agent_storage_path instead of home_storage_path. When paths differ (common for users with persistence_base configured), the home sqsh was placed where only agents are expected, causing mount failure. Now reads home_storage_path and persistence_base from config separately. Also searches all relevant paths for legacy IMG files and raw folders.

## 2026.04.16.26
- Fix: Background migration hung the installer UI. The nohup backgrounded process kept file descriptors open, preventing the PLG install script from exiting. Added disown after the background launch to fully detach the migration process from the installer shell.

## 2026.04.16.25
- Fix: Removed test-harness.sh download from PLG. The dev test script was excluded from the public GitHub repo but still referenced as a FILE download in the PLG, causing install failure on production servers pulling from GitHub.

## 2026.04.16.24 - The "Storage Intelligence" Update
- Feat: SquashFS Storage Architecture - Replaced Btrfs loopback images with a layered SquashFS + ZRAM overlay system. Agent binaries and home directories now use compressed read-only layers with a RAM write buffer, dramatically reducing Flash USB wear while maintaining instant persistence. Automatic layer consolidation keeps storage footprint minimal.
- Feat: Array-Aware Storage - The plugin now detects when configured storage paths depend on the Unraid array or pools. When the array is stopped, a Storage Unavailable overlay guides users through emergency options. When the array starts, the plugin automatically restores normal operation with no manual intervention needed.
- Feat: Emergency Mode - When all storage is on the stopped array, users can install a temporary AI agent directly into RAM and launch an emergency terminal session. OpenCode is recommended as it requires no authentication. Temporary agents and sessions are automatically cleaned up when the array restarts.
- Feat: Agent Version Management - Replaced the simple Stable/Preview toggle with a full version picker dropdown per agent. Browse all available versions with tagged releases and stable versions within a configurable time window. Supports upgrade, downgrade, and channel selection (latest, next, beta, etc). Update notifications appear via Unraid built-in notification system on a configurable schedule.
- Feat: Configurable Storage Locations - Home and agent storage paths can now be independently configured and migrated between Flash, array shares, cache pools, and unassigned devices. A guided migration flow persists data, copies files with progress tracking, and consolidates at the destination.
- Feat: Array Stop Warning - When stopping the array, a warning dialog lists affected AI sessions and storage paths. Users can choose to proceed (sessions are terminated gracefully) or cancel. Sessions on non-array paths continue running uninterrupted.
- Feat: Docker Tool Wrappers - Integrated proxy scripts for Docker-based tools (e.g. semgrep). When an agent requests a tool, it transparently runs via Docker container with clear install instructions if the image is not available.
- Improve: Settings Page Performance - The Agent Store tab no longer blocks on npm registry queries during page load. Version data is cached and refreshed in the background, making the settings page load instantly.
- Improve: Install Progress Resilience - Agent install and update progress bars now survive page refreshes. If you navigate away and return during an installation, the progress bar resumes from where it left off.
- Improve: Storage Migration Safety - Consolidation is skipped when source or target is on Flash USB to avoid unnecessary write amplification. Config file writes are serialized to prevent corruption from concurrent operations.
- Improve: Real-Time Status Updates - Storage status changes (array start/stop) are detected via Nchan for instant UI updates, with a polling fallback for reliability. Page reloads no longer trigger the browser unsaved changes dialog.
- Fix: Terminal clipboard and right-click behavior restored to browser defaults.
- Fix: Storage path availability detection now correctly identifies when array shares are inaccessible.
- Fix: Home storage path setting now correctly applies to home operations.

## 2026.04.06.54
- Feat: Full-Screen Terminal Overlay - Added a dedicated 'Temporary Terminal' accessible directly from the agent drawer. This provides a blur-backed, full-screen bash session synchronized with your active workspace directory for manual CLI operations.
- Feat: Ready-Now Workspace Performance - Implemented 'Boot-time Resurrection' which proactively pre-loads all AI agent binaries and user home RAM volumes during system startup or installation. This eliminates the restoration delay previously encountered on first use.
- Improve: Terminal-to-Workspace Synchronization - Switching between workspace tabs now automatically reloads all terminal sessions (both overlay and tab-based) to ensure the path always matches the visible project.
- Improve: Btrfs Storage Resilience - Hardened the agent storage lifecycle with mandatory auto-mounting and namespace verification, ensuring reliable binary availability even after unexpected system reboots.
- Improve: UI Initialization Feedback - Added a descriptive 'Restoring Home Storage' overlay to the terminal interface to provide users with visual status during the first background restoration of persistent data to RAM.
- Fix: Loopback Image Stability - Optimized the Btrfs storage floor and headroom constraints to prevent 'No space left' (ENOSPC) errors during image resizing, and ensured storage locks are correctly enforced after maintenance cycles.

## 2026.04.04.05
- Improve: Storage Intelligence - Implemented advanced Btrfs management including tail-block evacuation for reliable image shrinking, intelligent expansion guards to protect Flash drive headroom, and automated self-healing for corrupted loopback images.
- Improve: UI &amp; UX Refinement - Redesigned the Agent Store and configuration drawers with a high-density layout, improved spacing, and automated drawer management for a smoother workspace transition.
- Improve: Terminal Resilience - Significantly hardened terminal session stability and connection reliability through improved user isolation and robust environment variable propagation.
- Improve: Diagnostics &amp; Transparency - Enhanced the storage dashboard with "Truthful Capacity Reporting" showing both logical data size and physical disk footprint, along with better error visibility for system maintenance tasks.
- Fix: Storage Permissions - Resolved edge cases where agent storage could become write-protected or inaccessible due to kernel-level loopback locks.

## 2026.03.28.05
- Improve: Data Integrity - Implemented SQLite 'Surgical Repair' (PRAGMA integrity_check) and automated pre-flight recovery for OpenCode and Claude agent databases.
- Improve: Performance - Drastically reduced plugin upgrade time and periodic sync latency on USB Flash drives by implementing '--size-only' rsync and excluding non-essential caches (.npm, .bun).
- Security: Replaced 'eval' command execution with safe Bash array-based execution in the terminal wrapper to eliminate arbitrary code execution risks.
- Fix: PHP 8.0+ Compatibility - Resolved 'unlink' warnings and improved custom error handling to correctly respect the suppression operator (@).
- Fix: Upgrade Reliability - Added automated RAM-to-Flash backup and SQLite 'wal_checkpoint' during plugin updates to ensure zero data loss.

## 2026.03.27.20
- Fix: Critical XML Validation (Escapes raw ampersands in changelogs to resolve 'XML parse error' failures).
- Fix: Switched to high-fidelity literal replacement logic for public releases to prevent corrupted .plg structure.

## 2026.03.27.19
- Feat: Added Shell Integration aliases for all agents (kilo, pi, codex, droid, nanocoder).
- Fix: Resolved 'Status not available' by fixing GitHub URL extraction for SSH-over-443 remotes.
- Fix: Corrected changelog replacement to prevent symbol corruption during publishing.

## 2026.03.27.18
- Feat: Added Support for OpenCode, Claude Code, and NanoCoder agents.
- Feat: Global Shell Integration providing native 'claude', 'gemini', and 'opencode' aliases in all SSH and local terminal sessions.
- Feat: Integrated "User &amp; Architecture Guide" links within the Settings page and Terminal Drawer for instant help access.
- Improve: Terminal Stability with optimized shell environment propagation and automated SQLite self-healing for agent history.
- Fix: Reinforced recursive permission enforcement for agent binaries to prevent 'Permission denied' / EACCES errors in RAM.

## 2026.03.18.01
- Feat: Added Factory CLI (@factory/cli) support
- Feat: Integrated 'droid' binary and Factory session management
- UI: Added Factory icon and updated agent registry

## 2026.03.17.35 - The "Professional Workspace" Update
- Feat: Advanced Workspace Environment Management - New "Manage ENV" drawer overlay allows viewing and overriding global API keys per workspace without affecting global settings.
- Feat: Intelligent API Persistence - Dynamically discovers and persists API keys for all installed agents (OpenCode, Kilo Code, etc.) in the Secrets Vault.
- Feat: Hybrid Home Persistence - Implemented a decoupled background sync daemon that asynchronously mirrors the high-performance RAM home directory to the Flash drive.
- Feat: Multi-User Migration - Seamlessly migrates AI agent data when switching the active Unraid user, ensuring chat history is preserved.
- Improve: Premium UI Theming - Unified orange button theme, consistent card layouts, and professional blue-sidebar help styling throughout the manager.
- Improve: Performance &amp; Stability - Optimized terminal initialization to eliminate 502 Bad Gateway errors and implemented atomic locking for background sync operations.
- Improve: Clipboard Synchronization - Enabled OSC 52 support for dual-direction clipboard synchronization between the AI terminal and your browser.
- Improve: TrueColor Support - Full 24-bit TrueColor environment propagation across the entire terminal stack for better syntax highlighting.
- Fix: Terminal Rendering - Resolved scrolling and corruption issues in terminal sessions, particularly for limited-user contexts.
- Fix: Setting Persistence - Ensured fallback API keys and backup schedule settings correctly persist between reboots and user changes.
- Fix: Environment Visibility - Resolved a critical bug where custom environment variables and Secrets Vault keys were not correctly propagated to the active AI agent.

## 2026.03.09.19 - The "Premium UX" Update
- Feat: Expanded Agent Store - Added support for Claude Code, OpenCode, Kilo Code, Pi Coder, and Codex CLI.
- Feat: Integrated Node.js Environment - Bundled Node.js (v22.22.0) with npm for seamless, portable agent management.
- Feat: Premium Uninstaller UI - Completely redesigned uninstallation with quiet logging and a resilient, high-contrast summary box confirming preservation of settings and chats.
- Feat: Premium Installer UX - Polished installation flow with professional status updates and a new "INSTALL COMPLETE" visual summary.
- Improve: System Branding - Unified all system notifications and UI elements under the "AI CLI Agents Plugin" title.
- Improve: Boot Resiliency - Implemented persistent USB source caching for instant UI availability on reboot.
- Improve: Hardware Optimization - Moved all runtime logs to RAM (/tmp) to minimize USB flash drive wear.
</CHANGES>


